===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|heven|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|heofon||heaven, sky|lang=ang}}, from {{proto|Germanic|himinaz||himilaz|heaven, sky|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|k(')em-en-||k(')em-er-|sky, cloud|lang=en}}, from {{proto|Indo-European|title=Proto-Indo-European base|ḱam-|cover, shroud, clothes|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|Heven||heaven, sky|lang=nds}}, {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term|heƀan||heaven, sky|lang=osx}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|himinn||heaven, sky|lang=non}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|||tr=himins|heaven, sky|lang=got}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|hemel||heaven|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Himmel||heaven|lang=de}}, and perhaps {{etyl|cy|-}} {{term|cwmwl||cloud|lang=cy}}, {{etyl|kw|-}} {{term|kommol||cloud|lang=kw}}, {{etyl|br|-}} {{term|koumoul||cloud|lang=br}} – unless all these three reflect a borrowing of {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|cumulus||heap|lang=la}} into Proto-British instead, compare Modern English {{term|cumulus||a type of cloud|lang=en}}. Related to {{l|en|chemise}}.

